 package, but I’m wondering if this should be public. The developer's requirement for public top-level test classes makes me question if support files can be public too. There’s guidance about mapping classes to test files, but that might not fully prohibit adding support Java files. Perhaps generating class bytes at runtime is an alternative, but I'm unsure if that fits within restrictions given the constraints on the ClassLoader.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring ClassLoader customization**\\n\\nI’m considering subclassing ClassLoader and overriding the loadClass method to return a class literal for names like ImplementationObjectFactory. I realize that if the original loadClass call site runs, it will succeed, yet it refers to the class loader of ObjectFactory unless a custom loader was used. For contextPath variants, passing a custom class loader could allow returns for ObjectFactoryImplementation. However, creating a public ObjectFactory in a separate package might complicate things. Dynamic class loading is tricky and potentially unsupported, so I’m leaning toward using the existing package class instead.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering ObjectFactory implementation**\\n\\nI’m contemplating whether to nest the impl ObjectFactory in the same package, but I think using a separate support class may be more effective. I wonder if the unsupported property is necessary if the context is succeeding faster. I must ensure that JAXBContext.newInstance works under Native conditions, as it might require metadata for test class annotations. In the GRM tests, the native image is built with metadata from JVM tests, so test classes might include that. Ideally, I could load successfully and then deliberately fail before delegating to simplify things.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating ObjectFactory and Library Class Access**\\n\\nI’m thinking about supporting the class name ObjectFactory instead of test, which might be okay. I need to consider that the user-code filter currently includes only com.sun.tools.xjc. The agent's conditional configuration may not cover test packages, but it seems like dynamic coverage of the library class should still collect the stack. It doesn’t necessarily need metadata for support. I wonder if we need to ensure a successful load in the custom class loader. Let's modify that.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_spTaB6s7FjrNcCay9LwMKK0Z|fc_0eb0aa1354b923450169fe45b018fc8191a83250db96ac8851", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/org.glassfish.jaxb/jaxb-xjc/4.0.6/src/test/java/org_glassfish_jaxb/jaxb_xjc/impl/ObjectFactory.java", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage org_glassfish_jaxb.jaxb_xjc.impl;\n\npublic final class ObjectFactory {\n    public ObjectFactory() {\n    }\n}\n"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1736, "output": 962, "cacheRead": 35328, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 38026, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778271646101, "responseId": "resp_0eb0aa1354b923450169fe45a12f0c8191a5d52c7ef1a38b95"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_spTaB6s7FjrNcCay9LwMKK0Z|fc_0eb0aa1354b923450169fe45b018fc8191a83250db96ac8851", "toolName": "write", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "Successfully wrote 318 bytes to tests/src/org.glassfish.jaxb/jaxb-xjc/4.0.6/src/test/java/org_glassfish_jaxb/jaxb_xjc/impl/ObjectFactory.java"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1778271665050}]}
